    "lp_biology": {
      "type": "aliange-lp-text-block",
      "blocks": {
        "s1": {
          "type": "subheading",
          "settings": {
            "text": "1. The Collagen Cliff"
          }
        },
        "t1": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "body": "<p>Collagen is the structural protein that gives your skin firmness and bounce. From your mid-20s, collagen production declines by about 1% every year. By the time you reach 40, this cumulative loss becomes visibly apparent. The skin matrix begins to weaken, leading to the formation of fine lines, deeper wrinkles, and a loss of structural volume.</p>"
          }
        },
        "s2": {
          "type": "subheading",
          "settings": {
            "text": "2. Slowed Cellular Turnover"
          }
        },
        "t2": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "body": "<p>In your 20s, your skin cells naturally renew every 28 days, constantly pushing fresh, luminous cells to the surface. After 40, this cycle can slow down dramatically, taking up to 45–60 days. This buildup of dead, senescent cells on the surface is the primary cause of the dull, lacklustre complexion often associated with mature skin.</p>"
          }
        },
        "s3": {
          "type": "subheading",
          "settings": {
            "text": "3. Barrier Depletion and Hormonal Shifts"
          }
        },
        "t3": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "body": "<p>As we enter perimenopause and menopause, declining estrogen levels lead to a reduction in sebum production and hyaluronic acid synthesis. The skin's protective lipid barrier becomes compromised, resulting in chronic dehydration, increased sensitivity, and a feeling of tightness that no standard moisturiser seems to resolve.</p>"
          }
        }
      },
